To fix the SQL injection vulnerability in the code snippet, you should use parameterized queries instead of directly concatenating user input into the SQL query string. Parameterized queries separate the SQL query logic from the user input, thus preventing malicious input from altering the structure of the SQL query.

Here is an updated version of the code using a parameterized query:

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class SQLInjectionFixed {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Get user input
            String userInput = "'; DROP TABLE users; --";

            // Connect to the database
            Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection("jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydatabase", "username", "password");

            // Use a parameterized query to prevent SQL injection
            String query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ?";
            PreparedStatement stmt = conn.prepareStatement(query);
            stmt.setString(1, userInput);

            // Execute the SQL query
            ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery();

            // Process the results
            while (rs.next()) {
                System.out.println(rs.getString("username"));
                System.out.println(rs.getString("email"));
            }

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
``

